<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="color: #b23233;"><em><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269310" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/princessbride-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="princessbride" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269310" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/princessbride-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" />The Princess Bride</em></span></strong><br />
dir. Rob Reiner, 1987</h1>
<h5></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>William Goldman’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780156035156" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Princess Bride</a> </em>(1973)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong>Your Bisexual Awakening • Cult Movies of Unusual Resonance(s) • Endlessly Quotable • Peak Patinkin</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>There are few films with a higher delight-to-runtime ratio than <em>The Princess Bride</em>. Its particular alchemy of postmodern irreverence and slapstick buffoonery has made it an enduring cult classic despite its initially underwhelming box office returns. Of course, it benefits from being adapted by Goldman himself—not so often is the author of the source text also an Academy Award-winning screenwriter—and from the fact that it was a particular passion project for Reiner, whose father had given him the book, and who was determined to adapt it despite the fact that Hollywood considered it unadaptable.</p>
<p>“When I first met Bill Goldman to talk about this,” <a href="https://www.goldderby.com/film/2025/the-princess-bride-rob-reiner-how-movie-was-made/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Reiner remembered,</a> “he said, ‘This is my favorite thing I&#8217;ve ever written, and I want this on my tombstone. And what are you going to do with it?’” Well, we all know the answer to that. –<em>Emily Temple, Managing Editor</em></p>
